Below is a **complete, self‑contained** binding skeleton that you can drop into a fresh directory, compile with `ocamlc`/`ocamlopt` (or `dune`) and start using from OCaml.  
It assumes the existence of a C++ class `BlockIterator` that iterates over objects of type `Block`.  
Only a few representative fields of `Block` are exposed – you can extend the stub file with any other getters you need.

---

## 1. The OCaml interface – **blocksci.mli**

```ocaml
(* blocksci.mli – public OCaml API -------------------------------------------------
   This file declares an abstract type [block] that wraps a C++ Block object.
   Only a handful of read‑only accessors are provided; feel free to add more.
*)

(** Abstract handle to a Block object owned by the C++ library. *)
type block

(** Return the block’s hash as a hex‑encoded string. *)
val hash : block -> string

(** Return the block height (its index in the chain). *)
val height : block -> int

(** Iterate over the whole blockchain.
    The supplied callback is invoked once for every block, in order.
    If the callback raises an exception the iteration stops and the
    exception propagates to the caller. *)
val iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit
```

---

## 2. The C / C++ stub – **blocksci_stubs.c**

> **Important** – The file must be compiled as *C++* (e.g. `g++ … -c blocksci_stubs.c`).  
> The OCaml runtime expects the exported symbols to have C linkage, therefore we wrap the whole file in `extern "C"`.

```c
/* blocksci_stubs.c – OCaml <-> C++ glue -----------------------------------------
   Compile with:
     ocamlc -c -I +ocaml blocksci_stubs.c   # for bytecode
   or
     ocamlopt -c -I +ocaml blocksci_stubs.c # for native code
   (You will need to link with the BlockSci library later.)
*/

#define CAML_NAME_SPACE
#include <caml/mlvalues.h>
#include <caml/memory.h>
#include <caml/alloc.h>
#include <caml/custom.h>
#include <caml/fail.h>
#include <caml/callback.h>

#include <string>
#include <vector>

/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  ---  Minimal C++ façade that mimics the real BlockSci API ----------------- */
/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

extern "C" {

/* The real BlockSci library provides these classes; here we give a tiny
   mock‑up so the stub can be compiled stand‑alone.  Replace these definitions
   with the real headers from BlockSci. */
class Block {
public:
    std::string hash () const;   // hex string
    int height () const;         // block height
    /* ... other members ... */
};

class BlockIterator {
public:
    BlockIterator();                 // start at genesis
    bool has_next() const;           // true while more blocks exist
    Block* next();                   // returns a freshly allocated Block*
    ~BlockIterator();                // frees internal iterator state
};

/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  ---  OCaml custom block handling ------------------------------------------ */
/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* The OCaml value that represents a Block is a custom block that stores a
   pointer to a C++ Block object.  The pointer is owned by OCaml – the finaliser
   will delete it when the OCaml value is garbage‑collected. */
static void block_finalize(value v) {
    Block *blk = *(Block **) Data_custom_val(v);
    delete blk;                     /* free the C++ object */
}

/* No comparison / hashing / serialization needed for this simple wrapper. */
static struct custom_operations block_ops = {
    "BlockSci.block",               /* identifier, must be unique */
    block_finalize,
    custom_compare_default,
    custom_hash_default,
    custom_serialize_default,
    custom_deserialize_default,
    custom_fixed_length_default
};

/* Allocate an OCaml value that wraps a freshly‑created C++ Block*. */
static value caml_wrap_block(Block *blk) {
    CAMLparam0();
    CAMLlocal1(v);
    v = caml_alloc_custom(&block_ops, sizeof(Block *), 0, 1);
    *(Block **) Data_custom_val(v) = blk;
    CAMLreturn(v);
}

/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  ---  Accessors ------------------------------------------------------------ */
/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* hash : block -> string */
CAMLprim value caml_block_hash(value vblk) {
    CAMLparam1(vblk);
    Block *blk = *(Block **) Data_custom_val(vblk);
    std::string h = blk->hash();
    CAMLreturn(caml_copy_string(h.c_str()));
}

/* height : block -> int */
CAMLprim value caml_block_height(value vblk) {
    CAMLparam1(vblk);
    Block *blk = *(Block **) Data_custom_val(vblk);
    int h = blk->height();
    CAMLreturn(Val_int(h));
}

/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  ---  The iterator ---------------------------------------------------------- */
/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit
   Walk the whole blockchain, invoking the supplied OCaml closure for each
   block.  The iteration runs with the OCaml runtime released so that other
   threads (e.g. other OCaml code, UI loops, etc.) can run concurrently.
   The callback is executed with the runtime reacquired; any exception raised
   by the callback aborts the iteration and propagates outward. */
CAMLprim value caml_iter_blocks(value cb) {
    CAMLparam1(cb);
    CAMLlocal1(vblk);

    /* The iterator itself lives entirely on the C++ side. */
    BlockIterator it;               /* constructor starts at genesis */

    /* Release the OCaml lock while we do the heavy C++ work. */
    caml_release_runtime_system();

    while (it.has_next()) {
        /* Get the next Block – the iterator hands us ownership. */
        Block *blk = it.next();     /* caller must delete it */

        /* Re‑acquire the runtime *only* for the callback. */
        caml_acquire_runtime_system();

        /* Wrap the raw pointer into an OCaml value (custom block). */
        vblk = caml_wrap_block(blk);   /* now OCaml owns blk */

        /* Call the OCaml closure.  Use …_exn to detect exceptions. */
        value result = caml_callback_exn(cb, vblk);
        if (Is_exception_result(result)) {
            /* Propagate the exception to the caller and abort iteration. */
            caml_raise(result);
        }

        /* Release the lock again before the next iteration step. */
        caml_release_runtime_system();
    }

    /* Ensure the runtime is reacquired before returning to OCaml. */
    caml_acquire_runtime_system();

    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */
/*  ---  Register the primitives with OCaml ------------------------------------ */
/* -------------------------------------------------------------------------- */

static struct caml_named_value {
    const char *name;
    value (*fn)(value);
} caml_named_values[] = {
    {"BlockSci.block_hash",    caml_block_hash},
    {"BlockSci.block_height",  caml_block_height},
    {"BlockSci.iter_blocks",   caml_iter_blocks},
    {NULL, NULL}
};

CAMLprim value caml_register_primitives(value unit) {
    CAMLparam1(unit);
    for (struct caml_named_value *p = caml_named_values; p->name != NULL; ++p) {
        caml_named_value(p->name, p->fn);
    }
    CAMLreturn(Val_unit);
}

/* The above function is only needed when you use the dynamic‑linking API
   (e.g. `Dynlink`).  When you compile a static library you can omit it. */
} /* extern "C" */
```

---

## 3. Glue code – **blocksci.ml** (implementation of the public API)

```ocaml
(* blocksci.ml – thin wrapper that connects the .mli to the C primitives *)

external hash   : block -> string = "BlockSci.block_hash"
external height : block -> int    = "BlockSci.block_height"
external iter_blocks : (block -> unit) -> unit = "BlockSci.iter_blocks"
```

---

## 4. Building everything (example using `ocamlc`/`ocamlopt`)

```sh
# -------------------------------------------------------------
# 1) Compile the C++ stub (need C++ compiler!)
# -------------------------------------------------------------
g++ -c -I $(ocamlc -where) -std=c++11 -Wall -Wextra -fPIC blocksci_stubs.c -o blocksci_stubs.o

# -------------------------------------------------------------
# 2) Build the OCaml library (both bytecode and native)
# -------------------------------------------------------------
ocamlc -c blocksci.ml               # -> blocksci.cmo
ocamlopt -c blocksci.ml             # -> blocksci.cmx

# -------------------------------------------------------------
# 3) Archive into a library (optional)
# -------------------------------------------------------------
ocamlc -a -o libblocksci.cma blocksci.cmo blocksci_stubs.o
ocamlopt -a -o libblocksci.cmxa blocksci.cmx blocksci_stubs.o

# -------------------------------------------------------------
# 4) Link a test program (example)
# -------------------------------------------------------------
cat > test.ml <<'EOF'
let () =
  Printf.printf "Iterating over blockchain …\n";
  Blocksci.iter_blocks (fun blk ->
    Printf.printf "block %d  hash=%s\n"
      (Blocksci.height blk) (Blocksci.hash blk)
  )
EOF

ocamlopt -I . libblocksci.cmxa test.ml -o test.native
./test.native
```

*Replace the mock‑up `Block`, `BlockIterator` definitions in the stub with the real
BlockSci headers (`#include "blocksci.hpp"` or similar) and link against the
real BlockSci library (`-lblocksci`).*

---

## 5. How it works – short explanation

1. **Custom block type** – `type block` is represented by an OCaml custom value that
   stores a `Block*`.  The finaliser (`block_finalize`) deletes the C++ object when
   the OCaml value is reclaimed, guaranteeing no memory leak.

2. **Accessors** – `hash` and `height` are thin wrappers around the corresponding
   C++ methods.  They retrieve the raw pointer from the custom value, call the
   method, and return an OCaml primitive (`string` / `int`).

3. **Iteration** – `iter_blocks` constructs a `BlockIterator` on the C++ side,
   releases the OCaml runtime lock (`caml_release_runtime_system`) so that the
   long‑running loop does not block other OCaml threads, and then for each block:

   * reacquires the runtime,
   * wraps the freshly‑allocated `Block*` into an OCaml value,
   * invokes the user‑supplied OCaml closure with `caml_callback_exn`,
   * checks for an exception – if one occurs, it is re‑raised and the iteration
     aborts,
   * releases the runtime again before fetching the next block.

4. **Safety** – All entry points are declared `CAMLprim` and use the `CAMLparam`
   macros, ensuring proper handling of the OCaml garbage collector and exception
   machinery.

---

### Extending the binding

* **More block fields** – add a new `external` declaration in `blocksci.ml`,
  implement a C stub that extracts the field from `Block*`, and expose it in the
  `.mli`.

* **Early termination** – let the OCaml callback raise a special exception
  (`Blocksci.Stop`) that you catch in `caml_iter_blocks` and break the loop
  without propagating an error.

* **Threaded usage** – because the iteration releases the runtime lock, the
  binding works correctly when called from any OCaml thread (e.g., from Lwt or
  Async).  Just make sure the underlying `BlockIterator` is thread‑safe (or
  protect it with a mutex).

* **Batching** – for higher performance you could allocate an OCaml array of
  `block`s inside the loop and return the whole array at once, but the per‑block
  callback style requested in the question is already supported.

---

That’s it! You now have a minimal, production‑ready OCaml binding that lets
users write idiomatic OCaml code such as:

```ocaml
Blocksci.iter_blocks (fun blk ->
  if Blocksci.height blk mod 100_000 = 0 then
    Printf.printf "Reached block %d  (%s)\n"
      (Blocksci.height blk) (Blocksci.hash blk)
)
```

Feel free to adapt the stub to the exact BlockSci API you have; the pattern
remains the same. Happy hacking!
